By the Law of Sines on $\triangle ACX$, \[\frac{AX}{\sin 21^\circ} = \frac{21}{\sin \alpha}.\]By the Law of Sines on $\triangle BCX$, \[\frac{BX}{\sin 30^\circ} = \frac{28}{\sin \alpha}.\]Since $BX = AX + 28$, we have  \[\frac{AX + 28}{\sin 30^\circ} = \frac{28}{\sin \alpha}.\]Solving for $AX$, we get \[AX = 28\left(\frac{\sin 30^\circ}{\sin \alpha} - 1\right).\]Substituting the expression for $\sin \alpha$ from the first equation, we get \[AX = 28\left(\frac{\sin 30^\circ}{\frac{21\sin \alpha}{AX}} - 1\right) = 28\left(\frac{AX\sin 30^\circ}{21\sin \alpha} - 1\right) = 28\left(\frac{AX\sin 30^\circ}{21\cdot \frac{AX\sin 21^\circ}{21}} - 1\right) = 28\left(\frac{\sin 30^\circ}{\sin 21^\circ} - 1\right).\]Therefore, $AX = \boxed{12.1}$ (rounded to the nearest tenth).

